# Environment Configuration

Create a `.env` file in the essay-prompt-scraper directory with the following variables:

```bash
# Scraper Configuration
SCRAPER_CONCURRENT_REQUESTS=3
SCRAPER_DELAY_BETWEEN_REQUESTS=2000
SCRAPER_REQUEST_TIMEOUT=30000
SCRAPER_RETRY_ATTEMPTS=3
SCRAPER_RETRY_DELAY=5000

# Browser Configuration
BROWSER_HEADLESS=true
BROWSER_VIEWPORT_WIDTH=1920
BROWSER_VIEWPORT_HEIGHT=1080

# Output Configuration
OUTPUT_DIRECTORY=./data
OUTPUT_FORMATS=json,csv
OUTPUT_INCLUDE_METADATA=true
OUTPUT_INCLUDE_RAW_HTML=false

# Logging Configuration
LOG_LEVEL=info
LOG_FILE=./logs/scraper.log
LOG_CONSOLE=true

# Proxy Configuration (Optional)
PROXY_ENABLED=false
PROXY_LIST=proxy1:port,proxy2:port

# Rate Limiting
RATE_LIMIT_ENABLED=true
RATE_LIMIT_REQUESTS_PER_MINUTE=30

# User Agent Rotation
USER_AGENT_ROTATION=true
CUSTOM_USER_AGENTS=user-agent-1,user-agent-2
```

## Usage

The scraper will automatically load these environment variables if a `.env` file exists. You can also override them by setting the variables in your shell environment.

## Security Notes

- Never commit the `.env` file to version control
- Add `.env` to your `.gitignore` file
- Use environment variables for sensitive configuration
